{"type":"message","id":"4990e48b","parentId":"cb0e4479","timestamp":"2026-03-31T12:56:11.659Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_463bd8f640874f3d9a71d7de","toolName":"web_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"query\": \"802.11ax 802.11be DCM MCS 14 15 BPSK modulation mapping\",\n  \"provider\": \"tavily\",\n  \"count\": 5,\n  \"tookMs\": 1482,\n  \"externalContent\": {\n    \"untrusted\": true,\n    \"source\": \"web_search\",\n    \"provider\": \"tavily\",\n    \"wrapped\": true\n  },\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"fbcf5cbe43df72c6\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\n11-19-1262-15-00be-specification-framework-for-tgbe.docx\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"fbcf5cbe43df72c6\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://mentor.ieee.org/802.11/dcn/19/11-19-1262-15-00be-specification-framework-for-tgbe.docx\",\n      \"snippet\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"1e7ff77e48aed7fc\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nDCM+MCS0 for Nss=1 as defined in 802.11ax is a MCS in 802.11be. • The detailed MCS number for DCM+MCS0 is TBD. • This is an R1\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"1e7ff77e48aed7fc\\\">>>\",\n      \"score\": 0.6826801\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"b1fc6abe04c08178\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nIEEE 802.11be – Extremely High Throughput WLAN\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"b1fc6abe04c08178\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://web3.arxiv.org/pdf/2007.13401v1\",\n      \"snippet\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"20a5aed0d7a21255\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nIn IEEE 802.11ax, DCM is only applicable to the MCS. 0/1/3/4 and 1/2 spatial streams to satisfy the high-reliability requirements [3]. With the support of\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"20a5aed0d7a21255\\\">>>\",\n      \"score\": 0.58721006\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"106f278fcdb9f42c\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nIEEE 802.11be-2024\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"106f278fcdb9f42c\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_802.11be-2024\",\n      \"snippet\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"fbb127039fd13ebb\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\n| 802 series | | | | | --- | --- | | 802 | * .2 * .4 * .5 * .6 * .7 * .8 * .9 * .10 * .12 * .14 * .16 + WiMAX · d · e * .17 * .18 * .20 * .21 * .22 * .24\\\") | | 802.1 | * D * p * Q * Qav * Qat * Qay * Qaz * Qbb * w * X * AB * ad * AE * ag * ah * ak * aq * AS * AX (LACP) * BA | | 802.3 (Ethernet) | * -1983 * a * b * d * e * i * j * u * x * y * z * ab * ac * ad * ae * **af** * ah * ak * an * aq * **at** * au * av * az * ba * **bt** * bu * by * bz * ca\\\") * cb\\\") * cc\\\") * cd\\\") * ce\\\") * cg * ch * ck\\\") * cm\\\") * cn\\\") * cp\\\") * cq * cr\\\") * cs\\\") * ct\\\") * cu\\\") * cv * cw\\\") * cx\\\") * cy\\\") * cz\\\") * da\\\") * db\\\") * dd * de\\\") * df\\\") | | 802.11 (Wi-Fi) | * -1997 * legacy mode \\\"IEEE 802.11 (legacy mode)\\\") * a * b * c * d * e * f * g * h * i * j * k * **n** (Wi-Fi 4) * p * r * s * u * v * w * y * z * aa * **ac** (Wi-Fi 5) * ad (WiGig) * ae * af * ah * ai * aj * ak * aq * **ax** (Wi-Fi 6) * ay * az * ba * bb * bc * bd * **be** (Wi-Fi 7) * bf * bh * bi\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"fbb127039fd13ebb\\\">>>\",\n      \"score\": 0.37421933\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"fa08ccded9eddf00\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nWi-Fi 7 MCS Table\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"fa08ccded9eddf00\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://semfionetworks.com/blog/wi-fi-7-mcs-table/\",\n      \"snippet\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"734f572e35707f3d\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\n802.11be, data rates, MCS, Wi-Fi 7. The blog post discusses the new sets of data rates that became available with 802.11ax (Wi-Fi 6) and explains how these Wi-Fi data rates are calculated. In this post, we will update the sets of Wi-Fi data rates to include the new data rates provided by the new 802.11be (Wi-Fi 7) standard. The following table includes all the MCSs data rates (up to 8 spatial streams) defined by the 802.11n (HT), 802.11ac (VHT), 802.11ax (HE) and **802.11be (EHT)** amendments:. I believe that this real world table will contain all of the Wi-Fi data rates we will use in enterprise networks:. As a reminder, here is the formula used to calculate Wi-Fi data rates with 802.11ax (Wi-Fi 6):. So now that we have this information, let’s try to understand the data rate that a typical Wi-Fi 7 device could use. * MCS Table (Update with 802.11ax data rates):. Not exactly as all the dara rates you see in this table are L2 Wi-Fi data rates.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"734f572e35707f3d\\\">>>\",\n      \"score\": 0.33737868\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"b8aa08dc21127c37\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nSetting new performance standards with IEEE 802.11bn\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"b8aa08dc21127c37\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://content.knowledgehub.wiley.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Setting-performance-standards-IEEE-802.11bn_wp_en_3610-2200-52_v0200.pdf\",\n      \"snippet\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"18c9edecedcda948\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\n... MCS and the MCS index was increased. The new. IEEE 802.11bn MCS fall between existing MCS. IEEE 802.11be had 16 MCS levels and changing the MCS index numbers.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"18c9edecedcda948\\\">>>\",\n      \"score\": 0.28241432\n    }\n  ]\n}"}],"details":{"query":"802.11ax 802.11be DCM MCS 14 15 BPSK modulation mapping","provider":"tavily","count":5,"tookMs":1482,"externalContent":{"untrusted":true,"source":"web_search","provider":"tavily","wrapped":true},"results":[{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"fbcf5cbe43df72c6\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\n11-19-1262-15-00be-specification-framework-for-tgbe.docx\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"fbcf5cbe43df72c6\">>>","url":"https://mentor.ieee.org/802.11/dcn/19/11-19-1262-15-00be-specification-framework-for-tgbe.docx","snippet":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"1e7ff77e48aed7fc\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nDCM+MCS0 for Nss=1 as defined in 802.11ax is a MCS in 802.11be. • The detailed MCS number for DCM+MCS0 is TBD. • This is an R1\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"1e7ff77e48aed7fc\">>>","score":0.6826801},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"b1fc6abe04c08178\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nIEEE 802.11be – Extremely High Throughput WLAN\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"b1fc6abe04c08178\">>>","url":"https://web3.arxiv.org/pdf/2007.13401v1","snippet":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"20a5aed0d7a21255\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nIn IEEE 802.11ax, DCM is only applicable to the MCS. 0/1/3/4 and 1/2 spatial streams to satisfy the high-reliability requirements [3]. With the support of\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"20a5aed0d7a21255\">>>","score":0.58721006},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"106f278fcdb9f42c\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nIEEE 802.11be-2024\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"106f278fcdb9f42c\">>>","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_802.11be-2024","snippet":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"fbb127039fd13ebb\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\n| 802 series | | | | | --- | --- | | 802 | * .2 * .4 * .5 * .6 * .7 * .8 * .9 * .10 * .12 * .14 * .16 + WiMAX · d · e * .17 * .18 * .20 * .21 * .22 * .24\") | | 802.1 | * D * p * Q * Qav * Qat * Qay * Qaz * Qbb * w * X * AB * ad * AE * ag * ah * ak * aq * AS * AX (LACP) * BA | | 802.3 (Ethernet) | * -1983 * a * b * d * e * i * j * u * x * y * z * ab * ac * ad * ae * **af** * ah * ak * an * aq * **at** * au * av * az * ba * **bt** * bu * by * bz * ca\") * cb\") * cc\") * cd\") * ce\") * cg * ch * ck\") * cm\") * cn\") * cp\") * cq * cr\") * cs\") * ct\") * cu\") * cv * cw\") * cx\") * cy\") * cz\") * da\") * db\") * dd * de\") * df\") | | 802.11 (Wi-Fi) | * -1997 * legacy mode \"IEEE 802.11 (legacy mode)\") * a * b * c * d * e * f * g * h * i * j * k * **n** (Wi-Fi 4) * p * r * s * u * v * w * y * z * aa * **ac** (Wi-Fi 5) * ad (WiGig) * ae * af * ah * ai * aj * ak * aq * **ax** (Wi-Fi 6) * ay * az * ba * bb * bc * bd * **be** (Wi-Fi 7) * bf * bh * bi\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"fbb127039fd13ebb\">>>","score":0.37421933},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"fa08ccded9eddf00\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nWi-Fi 7 MCS Table\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"fa08ccded9eddf00\">>>","url":"https://semfionetworks.com/blog/wi-fi-7-mcs-table/","snippet":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"734f572e35707f3d\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\n802.11be, data rates, MCS, Wi-Fi 7. The blog post discusses the new sets of data rates that became available with 802.11ax (Wi-Fi 6) and explains how these Wi-Fi data rates are calculated. In this post, we will update the sets of Wi-Fi data rates to include the new data rates provided by the new 802.11be (Wi-Fi 7) standard. The following table includes all the MCSs data rates (up to 8 spatial streams) defined by the 802.11n (HT), 802.11ac (VHT), 802.11ax (HE) and **802.11be (EHT)** amendments:. I believe that this real world table will contain all of the Wi-Fi data rates we will use in enterprise networks:. As a reminder, here is the formula used to calculate Wi-Fi data rates with 802.11ax (Wi-Fi 6):. So now that we have this information, let’s try to understand the data rate that a typical Wi-Fi 7 device could use. * MCS Table (Update with 802.11ax data rates):. Not exactly as all the dara rates you see in this table are L2 Wi-Fi data rates.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"734f572e35707f3d\">>>","score":0.33737868},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"b8aa08dc21127c37\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nSetting new performance standards with IEEE 802.11bn\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"b8aa08dc21127c37\">>>","url":"https://content.knowledgehub.wiley.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Setting-performance-standards-IEEE-802.11bn_wp_en_3610-2200-52_v0200.pdf","snippet":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"18c9edecedcda948\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\n... MCS and the MCS index was increased. The new. IEEE 802.11bn MCS fall between existing MCS. IEEE 802.11be had 16 MCS levels and changing the MCS index numbers.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"18c9edecedcda948\">>>","score":0.28241432}]},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774961771658}}
{"type":"message","id":"c97a73a3","parentId":"4990e48b","timestamp":"2026-03-31T12:56:24.264Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"从搜索结果看：\n1. 802.11ax 中 DCM 适用于 MCS 0/1/3/4\n2. DCM + MCS0 在 802.11be 中有对应的 MCS\n\n让我获取更详细的信息来回答用户的问题。","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2121fc77480e4ec38d2df955","name":"web_fetch","arguments":{"extractMode":"markdown","url":"https://web3.arxiv.org/pdf/2007.13401v1"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom-43-133-33-215-3000","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":53698,"output":148,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":53846,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774961771660,"responseId":"6f0b33044bf6d88176c9cb4d9fcbc707"}}
